      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-22T22:52:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Done",
      "parentUuid": "d9f7dbb2_5f2d751c",
      "revId": "8a7b65dc9e8973119c2ed6db733f8695d195d5f9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "58c6facf_a3a61b54",
        "filename": "compat/android/dlfcn_internal.cc",
        "patchSetId": 15
      },
      "lineNbr": 122,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-22T21:15:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "As mentioned previously, let’s not do NODEFER, since we’re so exceedingly unlikely to raise a SIGFPE from our handler. If one is raised, it’s probably not ours, and it’d be better to crash and look like a crash, than exit(1) mysteriously with minimal tracing possible.\n\nIn fact, if there’s a decent and concise way we can be assured that the signal came from our own code (or at least just that the expected thread is the one that faulted), it’d be a nice improvement. A check of the siginfo (in the style of Signals::WillSignalReraiseAutonomously) to assure that the signal came from hardware, along with a thread identity check, would probably be enough. But I’m also happy to not do this now, or to do it just as a follow-up. We can get this in now and then gussy it up later. Signal handlers are tricky enough as it is, we don’t have to solve the world today.",
      "revId": "8a7b65dc9e8973119c2ed6db733f8695d195d5f9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
